            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-285-person2137">
                  WILLIAM 
                  LAWRENCE
               <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2137" type="surname" value="LAWRENCE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2137" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2137" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I <rs id="t18311201-285-viclabel1517" type="occupation">keep <placeName id="t18311201-285-crimeloc1518">Serle's coffee-house, Carey-street, Lincon's Inn-fields</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-crimeloc1518" type="placeName" value="Serle's coffee-house, Carey-street, Lincon's Inn-fields"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-crimeloc1518" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-285-off1515 t18311201-285-crimeloc1518"></join>
                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-285-victim2136 t18311201-285-viclabel1517"></join>. On the evening of the 30th of November, the prisoner came into the coffee-room about a quarter before six o'clock; he staid there ten minutes or a quarter of an hour, had a glass of ale, and was going out, when I heard a sound of silver; I waited at the door, and allowed him to pass me, and saw obtruding from his right-hand coat pocket, a spoon or prong; I followed him: he began to run, and run towards Bell-yard - I came up and caught him by the collar; I heard some silver fall, and all the observation he made was, "I have no plate."</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. STURGEON. Q. You are not certain whether it was a spoon or a fork? A. No - he did not appear intoxicated.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-285-person2138">
                  JOHN 
                  WARREN KEETLEY
               <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2138" type="surname" value="WARREN KEETLEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2138" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2138" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live at Derby, and am a conveyancer. On the 30th of November I was sitting in the coffee-room, and saw a person walk across the room from the adjoining box, towards the door; he went about a yard past the table, in the centre of the room, which is used as a sideboard - he then took a number of spoons from the sideboard, went towards the door, and was putting them into his pocket - I was rising from my seat, and at that moment Mr. Lawrence opened the half door; the man ran out at the other door - two of the spoons fell from his hand or his pocket.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. You do not know that the prisoner is the man? A. No.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-285-person2139">
                  JOHN 
                  WEEKS
               <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2139" type="surname" value="WEEKS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2139" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-person2139" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am waiter to Mr. Lawrence. I saw the prisoner in my master's coffee-room - he had a glass of ale, and then asked me to give him another - I left the room to do so; there were some silver spoons on the centre table of the room - when I returned with the ale I picked up two spoons at the door; the prisoner was then just gone out, and my master after him - I took the two spoons to the table, and found that one was then missing.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Are you sure there were no forks among them? A. Not among the spoons; there were at another part of the table - he did not appear intoxicated.</p>

               <p>MR. LAWRENCE. I saw the prisoner stopped, without losing sight of him; the third spoon has not been found - these are the two.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was going out, but finding I had left my gloves upon the table I went back, and called for another glass of ale; finding I had had enough before I went out without it - I made a stumble, and pushed the spoons from the table on the floor.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18311201-285-verdict1519" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-verdict1519" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 21. - <rs id="t18311201-285-punish1520" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18311201-285-punish1520" type="punishmentCategory" value="imprison"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-285-defend2135 t18311201-285-punish1520"></join>
               Confined Three Weeks
            </rs>.</p>
